 crucial insights to our understanding of the United States as a nation of immigrants.Contributors: Leisy Abrego, JoAnn D'Alisera, Joanna Dreby, Yen Le Espiritu, Greta Gilbertson, Nazli Kibria, Cecilia Menjívar, Jennifer E. Sykes, Mary C. Waters, and Min Zhou.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aFamiliesxUnited States. 0aFamilieszUnited States. 0aImmigrant familiesxSocial conditionsxUnited States. 0aImmigrant familieszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 4aAcross. 4aGenerations. 4aStates. 4aUnited. 4abrings. 4acrucial. 4aimmigrants. 4ainsights. 4anation. 4aunderstanding. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aFoner, Nancy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814728468423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814728468.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK